It includes ambient sound so you dont have to take off your buds everytime some idiot interrupts you to tell you something very unnecessary and annoying though keeping ambient noise on all the time drastically reduces the battery life on the left ear so dont keep it on or else you will need to charge your left ear bud while using right. You can also find your earbuds with the help of the app. It also allows you to change what you want your buds to do when you tap on them. It also has sensors that detect if the buds are in your ear or not and stop music accordingly
One thing i dont like about buds+ is that its not mechanic but its a touchpad. Why would I use overpriced wireless earbuds, if the wired alternatives are waaayy cheaper, and the same-prized wired alternatives sound waaaayyy better?

If you already have good audio gear, but you want something you can use in random situations where you don't want to bother with the wire. I'm a big fan of wired audio and I love enjoying music on my Audio Technica headphones plugged into my DAC. But when I'm cooking, or buying groceries or on public transit I just don't want to have to bother with getting the knots out of wire every time I want to pull these out. I've done that for years, and sure you get good at it. But it's a hassle.

And on top of that, the wire of my daily driver earbuds never really survives more than a year. No matter how careful you are, at some point metal fatigue sets in and you will get intermittent contact as you move around.

It's just much more convenient to quickly pop in your wireless earphones, and you never have to worry about damaging the wire and only getting audio in one ear. If you have some disposable income, that convenience quickly outweighs the price difference.

To anyone using the Samsung Galaxy Buds+: Enable the "dynamic" profile in the Samsung Wear app. I was very disappointed with the audio quality when I first got them, but for some reason putting the audio preset to "dynamic" fixed that issue

It's still not audiophile grade audio, but I'll happily listen to music on these while working or doing chores or whatever. And the 11 hour battery life is just fantastic. You can use them in bed before going to sleep, accidentally fall asleep with them in your ears and they'll still have a couple hours of charge left by morning! I've managed to get the case down to 0% charge before, but I've never actually been in a situation where I forgot to charge and managed to drain both the case and earbuds.

I picked these up for 99 euros on the Dutch Amazon website. You'd be crazy to pay MSRP (~150) for these. At that price, I'd recommend these to anyone on Android who's looking for great all-rounders. You can go cheaper, but you'll have to make significant sacrifices...

So Linus gives the Galaxy Buds Live some grief for lack of a seal and poor noise cancellation, plus fitment in the ear issues.
I think he kind missed the point of them.
I detest in-ear canal earpieces and the Buds Live design I find super comfy. So much so that I've literally fallen asleep in bed with them in laying on my side and when I wake up they're still in and the ear on side I was laying on doesn't feel any discomfort or soreness.
The other factor is that these have an open designed body. Just like closed vs open backed gaming headsets. You don't get these for the isolation, you buy these if you want to also hear the outside world or don't like the closed in/pressure feeling in your ears that a sealed/closed design gives.
As both of those factors were my main reason for not having wireless buds up until now, when Samsung launched these, I was straight onto them, and I haven't been disappointed with my purchase.

Great video but I have to say I'm not on board with the whole wireless headphones thing. Well, it's more like I got onboard then got off the train two stops down the line. So far I've bought two sets of wireless earbuds (Xiomi Mi Sports + Samsung) and both suffered the same fate. Went jogging one day, started to sweat, the one side got lubricated enough to just pop out and go missing. When I bought a new phone last year, the S20 Plus, it still had the jack so I went back to wired and never looked back. Honestly, if you spend the same amount of money on a set of wired headphones, you get far better sound quality (by leaps and bounds) plus the added security of knowing if they do drop out for any reason, they're still attached to you. I'm not saying there isn't a place in the market for wireless headphones, but for me they're an over priced solution for a non-existent problem. They have their place in the market but the sacrifices they make are frankly too much for me to swallow.

I don't know about you guys, but music isn't worth listening to if it sounds like trash, so I would rather get only one hour of good music playback than four hours of a not so good music playback. The only acceptable codec is LDAC, which unfortunately even Sony's flagship earbuds cannot support. AAC is not now, nor has it ever been, nor will it ever be, an acceptable way to listen to music, full stop.

Full disclosure I have the Sony WF-1000XM3....someplace, I don't remember where I put them. I let all my friends listen to them, back when I could find them, and they all agreed that they sound like hot garbage once the bit-rate of a song goes beyond Spotify's "medium" option, unless you have Sony's AI enhancer thing turned on, in which case Spotify's "high-quality" option is okay. The same applies to any 320bit MP3 I had on Plex. This isn't only a Sony thing though, it's true for everyone. Fun fact, trying to play any flac audio though, even the many songs that do fall within or very close to Sony's 960kpbs LDAC BT5 codec and the earbuds just go haywire and sound garbled... because SONY'S FLAG SHIP EARBUDS, CANNOT USE SONY'S FLAGSHIP CODEC, EVEN WHEN PAIRED WITH SONY'S FLAGSHIP SMARTPHONE!
